a lenited form of <i>bychan</i>, a diminutive of <i>bach</i> ‘little’. This was often used to distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"RAABS","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Armin, Erwin, Frieda, Gerhardt, Kurt, Otto.","North German: habitational name from Labes or Labus in Pomerania. Compare   Labs  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Labs","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Gerhardt.","North German: variant of   Laabs  ."]}]},{"name":"Sophia","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Greek word meaning ‘wisdom’. The Eastern cult of  St Sophia  arose as a result of misinterpretation of the phrase Hagia Sophia ‘holy wisdom’ as if it meant ‘St Sophia’. The name became popular in England in the 17th and 18th centuries—the heroine of  Fielding's  novel Tom Jones (  1749 ) is called  Sophia Weston—and  has been increasing in popularity since the 1990s. In Scotland it has been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Beathag ."],"variants":[{"name":"Sofia","meanings":["variant spelling of   Sophia ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sophia VON RAABS was born in 1162, in Nuremberg, Rezat District, Bavaria, her father, Konrad von Raabs-Reidfeld II - Burgrave of Nuremberg, was 11 and her mother, Hildegard of Abenberg, was 25. She married Fredrick von Zollern-Nurnberg III - Burgrave of Nuremberg in 1184. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in 1218, in Middle Franconia, Bavaria, Germany, at the age of 56."},"et":{"1162–1218":"1162–1218","1188–Female":"1188–Surnud","1198–Female":"1198–Surnud","1139–1200":"1139–1200","1186–1261":"1186–1261","1200–1255":"1200–1255","1151–1190":"1151–1190","1138–1224":"1138–1224","1190":"1190","25 August 1190":"25. august 1190",